<HEAD><title>Freedom of Information Act -- Heritage PR</title>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg"><center>
<img src="/heritage/news.gif" height="111" width="576" alt="The Heritage Foundation News"><br></center>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>For Immediate Release</FONT></B><br>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>Contact: Heritage Public Relations<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=5>HERITAGE CALLS FOR CONGRESSIONAL FREEDOM OF INFORMATION ACT<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<B> <FONT SIZE=4>WASHINGTON, NOV. 15, 1996 --</FONT></B> The 105th
Congress should take full advantage of the revolution in telecommunications
technology to make available on the Internet all disclosable information
having to do with the laws it passes and how it conducts its business,
a pair of Heritage Foundation analysts <a href="/heritage/library/categories/govern/bg1098.html">said today</a>.
<P>
 According to <a href="/heritage/staff/weinstein.html">Kenneth R. Weinstein</a>, director of Heritage's Government
Reform Project, and research assistant August Stofferahn, &quot;By
taking the initiative in placing all disclosable information on
the Internet, Congress could avoid the contentious process of
specific requests for materials as well as the necessarily more
complex freedom of information procedures established for the
executive branch.&quot;
<P>
 In addition, the analysts say, the move would provide a needed
reform. &quot;Through key institutional and procedural reforms,
the 104th Congress sought to unmask and dismantle the network
of liberal special interests that ran Capitol Hill for decades,&quot;
Weinstein and Stofferahn said. &quot;A Congressional Freedom of
Information Act (CFOIA) would complete and confirm the move toward
open access to Congress.&quot;
<P>
 In addition to areas that already have been opened to the public
through the Internet -- such as THOMAS, the Library of Congress'
on-line legislative information service, and the GPO (Goverment
Printing Office) Access system, which features 58 information
databases produced by the federal government -- the U.S. House
of Representatives' Task Force on Committee Review already has
recommended that Congress' new open-door policy be expanded. Specifically,
the task force has called for amendments to bills, committee and
subcommittee prints and reports, and oversight plans and activities
to be placed on the Internet. Similarly, the U.S. Senate has sought
to use information technology to publicize its activities more
extensively through its &quot;Operation Daylight.&quot; 
<P>
 But Weinstein and Stofferahn say Congress should go further.
Under a CFOIA, all information currently made available to the
public would become available through the Internet. In addition
to the committee documents detailed by the House task force, Congress
would add issue briefs, spending reports, voting records, the
content of mass mailings, financial and lobbying disclosure documents,
and a host of other items.
<P>
 &quot;Providing citizens outside of Washington with the means
to closely examine and actively monitor the work of their elected
representatives would do more to foster openness and prevent back
room politics than any other single reform,&quot; the analysts
say. &quot;The 30 million American families with personal computers
would be able to use the Internet to observe more closely the
activities of Congress and their particular representatives. In
addition, other citizens could take advantage of the numerous
possibilities for Internet access at work and at public and university
libraries to find timely information on current legislation that
may affect their lives.&quot;
<P>
 &quot;Overall,&quot; Weinstein and Stofferahn say, &quot;these
changes would make our democratic system stronger and more responsive
to the average citizen.&quot;
<P>


<I><B><FONT SIZE=2>NOTE: Heritage Foundation research and publications
are available on the Internet through Town Hall <a href="http://www.townhall.com">(http://www.townhall.com)</a>
or directly through Heritage's homepage <a href="http://www.heritage.org">(http://www.heritage.org).</a>
The Town Hall site is the Internet home for many conservative
organizations in Washington. To retrieve articles from the Heritage
publications library, simply access the Heritage site, click on
the icon entitled &quot;Publications Library&quot; and choose
the policy area of interest.</FONT></B></I>
<P>
<I><B><FONT SIZE=2>&quot;NEXIS&quot; on-line-data-retrieval service
subscribers also can access Heritage studies. Heritage Foundation
reports (HFRPTS) can be found in the OMNI, CURRNT, NWLTRS, and
GVT group files on the NEXIS library and the GOVT and OMNI group
files of the GOVNWS library.<BR>
</FONT></B></I>
<P>
                                                             
                                                             
       
