<TITLE>Phillips Foundation Journalism Scholarships</TITLE>
<BODY>

<B>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE
<br>
CONTACT:</B> John Farley 301/340-7788, ext. 6090<p>
<br>
<br>
<CENTER><B><h2>PHILLIPS FOUNDATION ANNOUNCES 1996 JOURNALISM FELLOWSHIPS</h2>
<h3>$50,000 GOLD AWARD AND $20,000 SILVER AWARD</h3><br>
<hr size=3 width=50%></center><p>
Potomac, MD, May 7, 1996</b> -- The Phillips Foundation today announced the winners of its 1996 journalism fellowship awards.  Stacy Mattingly captured the $50,000 Gold Award for her proposal to write a book on a highly-charged school prayer case in northern Mississippi.  Daniel Richardson won the $20,000 silver award to write a series of articles on the growing Patriot movement in America.  
<p>
Mattingly and Richardson were introduced during an awards dinner last night at the University Club in Washington, D.C., attended by prominent journalists.
<p>
During her one-year fellowship which commences on September 1, 1996, Stacy Mattingly will research and write a book on <I>Lisa Herdahl v. Pontotoc County</I>, a Mississippi school prayer case currently in the courts.  Last year, she wrote an extensive article on the case for <I>The Oxford American </I>magazine in Mississippi.  She has spent a great deal of time in Pontotoc County, and her article was widely praised as the most thorough and balanced reporting on the case.  She will write a book in narrative form, beginning with the Herdahl family's move 
from Wisconsin to Mississippi and ending with the trial on the school prayer case.
<p>
Mattingly, 25, is a freelance journalist based in Atlanta.  She writes articles for <I>Crisis</I> magazine and the <I>Atlanta Journal-Constitution</I>.  She served as contributing editor and writer for <I>The Oxford American</I> and as staff reporter for <I>The Oxford Eagle</I> newspaper.  She graduated from Northwestern University with a B.A. in English.
<p>
For his fellowship project, Daniel Richardson will focus on the Patriot movement in this country.  He believes the Patriot "subculture" is becoming too large to be ignored.  He will investigate the many groups which comprise the Patriot subculture, and he will examine the single defining thread running through all Patriot ideas:  the subversion of the Constitution by internal and external foes leading to greater government authority at the expense of individual freedoms.
<p>
Richardson, 23, is a freelance journalist in Gresham, Oregon.  He writes articles and news stories for <I>The Oregon City News</I> and <I>East County Magazine</I> in Gresham.  He graduated from the University of Puget Sound last year with a B.A. in History.  For his senior thesis, he wrote "A Military History of the Hundred Years' War."
<p>
The Phillips Foundation is a non-profit organization founded in 1990 to advance the cause of objective journalism.  The Foundation established its journalism fellowship program in 1994 to provide annual grants for journalism projects supportive of American culture and a free society.  The fellowship program is open to working journalists with less than five years of professional experience.
<p>
The three Trustees of the Phillips Foundation served as judges for the competition.  The Trustees are:  Thomas L. Phillips, President of Phillips Publishing International, Inc.; Robert D. Novak, prominent national journalist and author of one of the longest running syndicated columns in the country; and Alfred S. Regnery, a Washington attorney and President of Regnery Publishing, Inc., a Washington, D.C.-based book publishing firm.
<p>
<br>
<center>[<a href="http://www.townhall.com">Town Hall</a>]</center>

