<html>
<title>Tax Limitation Constitutional Amendment - Tax Reform NOW!</title>
<BODY BGCOLOR="F5F5F5">

<b>From the Office of Representative Wally Herger<br>
2nd Congressional District, California</b>
<P>
CONTACT: STEVE THOMPSON<br>
(202) 225-3076</b>
<p>
<center>
   <h2>TAX LIMITATION CONSTITUTIONAL AMENDMENT</h2>	                
        <h3><I>PROTECTING FAMILIES FROM TAX-AND-SPEND WASHINGTON</I></h3>
<hr width=50%></center>
<p>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;	<b>WASHINGTON, D.C.</b> On April 15, the day Americans' increasingly burdensome tax bill is due, The House of Representatives will vote to make it harder to increase taxes in the future.  The <a href="http://rs9.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/z?c104:H.J.RES.159:">Tax Limitation Constitutional Amendment</a> would require a two-thirds vote in Congress to raise taxes rather than the fifty percent plus one currently required.
<p>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;	"In 1950, families paid only 5 percent of their income in federal taxes," said Herger.  "In 1990, that number jumped to 24 percent and when combined with state and local taxes, families lose almost half their income to taxes.  If a two-thirds tax increase amendment had been in place since 1980, the American people would have been spared more than $660 billion in new taxes, all of which were used to pay for more government spending."
<p>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;	"Over the past three decades, Washington has paid for wasteful and excessive federal spending by simply raising taxes on working families and small businesses," added Herger.  "These excessive taxes stifle business growth, hurt families, and hinder our nation's economy.  It shouldn't be easy to take money from families and businesses -- it's their money not Washington's."
<P>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;	"A two-thirds requirement to raise taxes would go a long way toward reining in runaway federal spending and putting a check on excessive taxation," said Herger.  "The requirement would also become a valued component in our efforts to reform the entire tax system."
<p>
<a href="http://rs9.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/z?c104:H.J.RES.159:">Read the full text</a> of the legislation
<P>
