<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Organizational Trends -- CRC</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/crc/images/bg.gif">
<a href="/crc/images/sidebar.map"><img src="/crc/images/sidebar.gif" alt="Navigation Bar"
 border="0" align="left" ISMAP></a>
<blockquote>
<center>
<img src="/crc/images/hdr-ot.gif">
</center>
<p>
<i>December,1996</i>
<P>
<h2>The CDC &quot;IMPACT&quot; Grant Program: Cash Cow for America's Health Charities?</h2>
<p>
For fifty years the federal government's Centers for 
Disease Control (CDC) in Atlanta has been concerned with curing disease through 
research, public education, and inoculation.  But recently the CDC has shifted its 
focus from the practice of medicine and medical research to politics.  The agency now 
spends tens of millions of taxpayers' dollars 
annually <I>to train lobbyists</I> in how to enact gun 
control laws, how to ban smoking or tobacco advertising, and other politically correct 
causes championed by the political left.
<P>It is illegal to use tax dollars for partisan politics, so there are serious concerns 
about not only the propriety but also the legality 
of the CDC's political initiatives.  This report examines a major ongoing program funded 
by the CDC that in 1993 alone spent $85 million in tax dollars to initiate a program in 32 
states and the District of Columbia to train 
lobbyists and build political coalitions that will 
advocate banning tobacco products.
<P>No one today denies the health hazards of smoking.  The issue here is not whether or 
not smoking is healthy; it is whether or not prohibition is wise public policy and, more 
importantly, whether or not tax dollars ought to 
be used to promote it.  
<P>Once tax dollars are used to promote one kind of &quot;politically correct&quot; consumption 
behavior, there is in principle no end to it.  Today, smoking happens to be the 
most politically incorrect behavior, but the consumption of fast foods, alcohol, red meat, 
and myriad other products has already been attacked by various self-appointed 
national nannies.  
BR>
<I>The author, Thomas J. DiLorenzo, is a Senior Fellow with the Capital 
Research Center and a Professor of Economics at Loyola College in Baltimore.</I><BR>

<P><B>Florida Leads the Way</B>
<P>1996 marks the midterm of a five year (1993-98) program sponsored by the CDC Office 
on Smoking and Health.  In 1993 the CDC awarded an initial $85 million to 32 state health 
departments as part of its &quot;National Tobacco 
Prevention an

d Control Program,&quot; which the agency labels 
<B>I</B>nitiatives to <B>M</B>obilize for the 
<B>P</B>revention <B>A</B>nd <B>C</B>ontrol of 
<B>T</B>obacco Use (IMPACT).  IMPACT grants to state 
health departments are renewable for up to five years.  
<P>At first blush there does not seem to be anything objectionable to state health 
departments helping people  especially children  quit smoking or discouraging 
them from taking up the habit in the first place.  
But the primary emphasis of the program is not medical treatment or education but politics. 
 The essential purpose of the grants is to mobilize a &quot;comprehensive and 
coordinated nationwide effort&quot; to enact 
prohibitionist legislation through &quot;local, state, and 
regional initiatives.&quot; 
<P>The grants fall into two categories:  
&quot;planning awards&quot; for states that have not 
yet established a political coalition, and 
&quot;core awards&quot; to assist states that have 
already established the political infrastructure 
for such a coalition.  The targeted states are listed in the accompanying box.
<P>Florida is one of the states that has received significant funding 
(approximately $250,000 per year since 1993) from the 
CDC's IMPACT program.  Because Florida is essentially a role model for what the CDC hopes 
to achieve in the other 31 states and the District of Columbia, it will be the focus of this report.  
<P>In its initial 1993 grant proposal to the CDC, the Florida Department of Health and 
Rehabilitative Services (FDHRS) &quot;project 
director,&quot; Mr. Joyner Sims, explained that 
the <HR>


 meetings,&quot; &quot;meeting room costs,&quot; the printing 
of a semi-annual coalition newsletter, and 
&quot;mini grants&quot; to local political coalitions 
throughout the state.
<P>The proposal also describes the precise role of the tax-funded Tobacco Free 
Florida Coalition.  The Coalition will &quot;Provide 
advocacy&quot; for &quot;tobacco prevention and 
control legislation,&quot; &quot;develop new legislation 
specifically targeting restrictions on outdoor 
advertising,<B>&quot; </B>and create<B> </B>a political 
&quot;training and technical assistance plan&quot; to 
provide &quot;coordinated support&quot; for lobbyists.  It 
will fund the travel of its members to political training conferences and establish &quot;a 
linkage with the Florida Association of Broadcasters.&quot;
<P>The Coalition will also seek to change Medicaid so that it covers &quot;tobacco 
cessation services&quot; that are provided by the 
health charities, among others.  This last policy objective would funnel millions of tax 
dollars to the major health charities.  Why should government subsidize smoking 
cessation when most smokers who quit (35 million 
by some estimates) do so on their own?
<P>Taxpayers' funds will also help finance the Coalition's participation in SCARCNet, 
an on-line communication network used by anti-smoking political activists that &quot;allows 
state officials to coordinate with CDC officials 
in countering major tobacco industry announcements.&quot;
<P>Florida's CDC grant application also makes clear the role of the major health charities 
 the ACS, American Heart Association (AHA), and American Lung 
Association (ALA)  and the political nature of the <HR>
<BR>
<B>For decades the political Left has used children as an 
excuse to enact public policies whose major effects are on adults. <HR>
</B><BR>
money would be spent mobilizing a &quot;Tobacco Free Florida Coalition.&quot;  At the 
time, this political coalition was known as 
&quot;The American Cancer Society's Lung Cancer 
Task Force,&quot; indicating that the apparent 
purpose of the grant was to use taxpayers' dollars 
to fund this ACS program.  The grant paid the salary for a &quot;Tobacco Free Florida 
Coalition Coordinator,&quot; a position that &quot;is located 
at the American Cancer Society (ACS) in Tampa, Florida,&quot; according to the grant contract.  
<P>Thus, even though the ACS has long denied receiving government funding of 
any kind (why should individuals donate if their tax dollars are already supporting the 
organization?), it does receive federal tax 
dollars that are filtered through the Florida 
health agency and, in all likelihood, through 
dozens of other state health departments as well.   
<P>In its application to the CDC, the FDHRS indicated that it intended to fill certain 
political &quot;gaps&quot; in the state, including the lack 
of a comprehensive statewide political coalition, limited funding for local 
coalition-building, local coalitions needing more direction 
in &quot;cultural diversity,&quot; and inadequate 
state government staff to help build political coalitions.
<P>If it received the CDC grant, the FDHRS promised to use its federal tax dollars to 
lobby for the following policies:
<P> Local ordinances that would ban smoking in the workplace;
<P> Educational campaigns for lawmakers;
<P> Bans on cigarette vending machines;
<P> Restrictions on tobacco products advertising;
<P> Tobacco excise tax increases, with some of the revenues earmarked for members of 
the Tobacco Free Florida Coalition
<P> Banning promotional give-aways of tobacco products
<P> Banning the sale of cigarettes by pharmacies; and
<P> Raising the legal smoking age to 21.
<P>The CDC grant would pay at least part of the salaries of Florida Health 
Department employees, American Cancer Society 
staff, and newly-hired political activists and consultants.  It also covers &quot;travel expenses 
for coalition members to attend quarterly
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 3 -->

IMPACT grant program in a table that lists Coalition personnel.  It shows that the 
health charities are effectively receiving 
taxpayers' dollars as Coalition members, and that 
arguably they are engaged in illegal, tax-funded political advocacy.  The FDHRS grant 
application lists the members of the Coalition and describes their roles (see box).
<P>The list of coalition members also includes medical professionals, but in virtually 
every instance their role is listed as liaison to 
fellow professionals, i.e., as political operatives.  
<P>
<P><B>The Role of the Robert Wood 
<P>Johnson Foundation</B>
<P>The Robert Wood Johnson Foundation (RWJF) in Princeton, New Jersey 
complements the CDC's political activities.  The Foundation was founded in 1972 and is 
the largest private foundation in the U.S. devoted exclusively to health care issues.  
Its assets approach $4 billion and its major 
health policy initiatives are almost exclusively 
aimed at drastically increasing the amount of government intervention in health care.
<P>Lawsuits filed against Hillary Rodham Clinton's secret health care task force 
have forced disclosure of the powerful influence RWJF exerted over the 
promotion of the Clinton administration's failed attempt at a government takeover 
of health care in 1993 and 1994.  
<P><B>STATES TARGETED FOR CDC IMPACT GRANTS</B>
<P>
<P>                      <B>Planning Award States                  Core Award States</B>
<P>________________________________________________________________________
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>________________________________________________________________________
<P>
<P>Source:  U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, Centers for Disease Control,   
              National Tobacco Prevention and Control Program,&quot; 1994.
<P>Alabama, Arizona, Arkansas, 
<P>Connecticut, Delaware, Georgia, 
<P>Kentucky, Mississippi, Nevada, Oregon, South Dakota, Tennessee, 
Wyoming, Vermont <BR>
In addition, RWJF's &quot;State Initiatives in Health Care Reform&quot; program put millions 
of dollars behind political lobbying efforts to pass state-level health care laws that 
contain such Clinton plan features as price 
controls, mandated managed care, &quot;community 
rating&quot; of health insurance, and massive regulation of health care markets.  Florida, 
Minnesota, and Washington passed legislation favored by the Foundation.  As 
Genevieve Young, an attorney specializing in 
health law, has argued in past issues of 
<I>Organization Trends</I>, these laws enable state 
officials to circumvent a U.S. Congress that is 
unwilling to do what the Administration and RWJF know is best.
<P>RWJF now wants to use these methods in the anti-smoking crusade.  In Florida and 
in twenty other states, RWJF is supplementing CDC taxpayer funding with its own 
&quot;Smokeless States&quot; grant program.   A brochure 
on the program indicates that the Foundation &quot;will make new grants to up to 21 
statewide coalitions working in partnership with 
community groups.&quot; RWJF plans to spend $20 million on the program over the next 
four years.
<P>To qualify for the RWJF grants, as Florida has, a state or nonprofit entity must 
demonstrate the existence of a &quot;strong, 
broad-based state-wide coalition,&quot; a &quot;state 
government commitment to the effort including 
support <BR>
Alaska, District of Columbia, Florida, Hawaii, Idaho, Illinois, Iowa, 
Kansas, Louisiana, Maryland, Montana, Nebraska, New Hampshire, 
North Dakota, Ohio, Oklahoma, Pennsylvania, Texas, Utah<BR>
from the governor, key legislators, and other public officials,&quot; and &quot;recent or 
proposed local and state policy and financing 
changes&quot; designed to achieve tobacco prohibition. 
 Despite occasional protests that they are not &quot;prohibitionists,&quot; prohibition is what 
RWJF and the health charities want.  What else, 
after all, can &quot;Smokeless States&quot; mean?
<P>In Florida, RWJF provides in-kind as well as financial support:  A FDHRS 
&quot;progress report&quot; to the CDC this year observes, 
&quot;The Robert Wood Johnson Foundation Advocacy Coordinators are assisting the 
[CDC] funded tobacco coalitions.&quot;  These 
&quot;advocacy coordinators&quot; organize media 
campaigns, conduct opinion polls, and train citizens in political advocacy.  The RWJF 
grant also is used in Florida to bring in 
&quot;nationally recognized experts in the tobacco 
control movement.&quot;  These efforts are 
consistent with the RWJF's record of attempting to &quot;solve&quot; public health problems with 
more government bureaucracy, regulation, and taxes.  
<P>
<P><B>Using Children as Political Pawns</B>
<P>For decades the political Left has used children as an excuse to enact public 
policies whose major effects are on adults.  The Children's Defense Fund, for example, 
spends virtually all its resources lobbying for an expanded welfare state.  But its name is 
useful when it chooses to attack critics of failed welfare state programs as &quot;anti-children.&quot;  
<P>The CDC and RWJF have adopted this strategy.  Even though most of their 
policy recommendations, such as higher excise 
taxes, affect everyone, they are careful to 
highlight <HR>
<BR>
<B>Is not something unsavory occurring when officials of 
the Florida Department of Education pay other peoples' children 
to entrap hard-working, tax-paying citizens?</B><BR>
<I>continued on page 4<HR>

<!-- Generation of PM publication page 4 -->

</I><BR>
<B>Organization</B>Trends<BR>
CDC &quot;IMPACT&quot;
<P><I>(continued from page 3)</I><BR>
 taxpayer funds are spent on public education programs, the 
lion's share goes toward tax-funded politics.  
From September 1993 to May 1994 the FDHRS boasted that it lobbied for a $1.00 increase 
in the state's tobacco products tax, working closely with the AHA lobbyist Scott Ballin. 
 This effort was unsuccessful.
<P>Florida could report success with the sting operations conducted by &quot;underage 
operatives who are observed by a special enforcement agent.&quot;  These resulted in the 
entrapment and citation of hundreds of convenience store clerks; dozens of 
businesses were subject to &quot;administrative actions&quot; 
that were taken against their business licenses; and a &quot;total of $136,000 in fees were 
collected for the Department of Education.&quot;
<P>Is not something unsavory occurring when officials of the Florida Department of 
Education pay other peoples' children to entrap hard-working, tax-paying citizens?  
Are Florida's law enforcement resources appropriately spent arresting clerks who sell 
cigarettes to teenagers?  Is criminalizing 
behavior the best way to advance public health?  
<P>Perhaps the most important political &quot;progress&quot; that Florida reported to the 
CDC is the news that the Tobacco Free Florida Coalition helped lobby for a new state law, 
SB 2110, which was enacted on May 25, 1994.  It allows the state to sue the tobacco 
industry to recover health care costs from tobacco-related illnesses incurred by Medicaid 
recipients.  Florida becomes one of fourteen 
states, as of this writing, pursuing this legal 
strategy and arguing that tobacco companies 
should be liable for the negative health effects 
of their product even if smokers know full well  as they undoubtedly do  that 
smoking increases health risks.
<P><B>TABLE 2
<P>Members of the Tobacco Free Florida Coalition</B>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>Don Webster
<P>John J. Brennan
<P>Sandra Kessler
<P>Dennis Valera
<P>Frederick Schild
<P>Beatrice Braun
<P>Hon. Higuel DeGrandy
<P>
<P>Hon. George Albright
<P>Beth Labasky
<P>Marcia Nenno<BR>
programs aimed at children.  In Florida and in other IMPACT states schoolchildren 
are encouraged (and sometimes paid) to join the Student Coalition Against Tobacco (SCAT). 
 A SCAT campaign involves students in a wide range of activities that organizers 
say are &quot;considered youth political advocacy, which is at the very base of 
the Student Coalition Against Tobacco.&quot;  
<P>The ACS, AHA, and ALA oversee SCAT activities, and they teach 
children to demonize their political opponents.  Join SCAT, children are 
told, and begin &quot;counteracting immoral tobacco industry tactics.&quot;
<P>There is nothing wrong with schoolchildren advising their friends to 
avoid smoking.  But SCAT pays junior high and high school students to 
conduct private sting operations, often against convenience stores.  SCAT reports 
that it sends &quot;minors out into the community in an attempt to purchase 
cigarettes either over the counter in retail outl<BR>
<B>Coalition Member               Organization Represented         Role in the Coalition</B>
<H1>

</H1>
<P>Source:  Florida Department of Health and Rehabilitative Services, Grant Proposal to 
<P>              Centers for Disease Control, 1993, obtained through Freedom of Information 
<P>              Act request.<BR>
ACS
<P>AHA
<P>ALA
<P>ACS
<P>Florida Medical Assoc.
<P>AARP
<P>Florida Hispanic Legislative Caucus
<P>State Legislator
<P>Registered Lobbyist
<P>ACS
<P>ets or from vending machines located in stores, restaurants, bars 
or other locations.&quot;  Such activities have become an integral part of the 
CDC's national coalition-building campaign even though some California law 
enforcement officials have criticized it as &quot;vigilantism.&quot;  
<P>Moreover, health charities are giving young SCAT recruits questionable 
information.  For example, one instructional guide advises children to &quot;make the public 
aware that young people are being attacked by toxins whenever we eat in a restaurant, 
play pool or bowl, or attend school.&quot;  There is 
no solid evidence that second-hand smoke is as hazardous as such a statement implies  
if, indeed, it is hazardous at all, being one of countless indoor pollutants.  Such 
language is needlessly frightening. 
<P>
<P><B>Political &quot;Progress&quot; in the War 
for Anti-Smoking Dollars</B>
<P>The CDC requires annual &quot;progress reports&quot; from the 32 states that receive 
its grants.  Florida's reports for 1993-95 show that although some<BR>
Legislative expertise
<P>Grassroots mobilization
<P>Grassroots mobilization
<P>Coalition builder
<P>Lobbying assistance
<P>Advocacy Services
<P>Legislative assistance
<P>
<P>Policy Making
<P>Legislative expert
<P>Coalition building
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 5 -->

<P>The logic of this argument, if it is accepted by the courts, is likely to have 
far-reaching effects.  It is not hard to imagine that 
plaintiffs' lawyers will file similar class-action 
lawsuits against the alcoholic beverage industry, the fast food business, and many 
other industries.  Overeating, overdrinking, even overexercizing can be hazardous to health.  
If courts reject the principle that adults are responsible for their own consumption 
behavior, the resulting liability crisis will 
rival the savings and loan crisis of the 1980s.
<P>The federal government's National Cancer Institute (NCI) has joined with the CDC 
to fulfill this promise.  NCI grant # CA-94-15 (obtained through a Freedom of 
Information Act request) provided $1,119,678 to 
Northeastern University Law School in Boston in 1995 for a four-year legal research project. 
 The project will &quot;produce policy papers&quot; 
on `states' ability to sue tobacco companies for the medical expenditures caused by 
tobacco-related diseases&quot; and paid by Medicaid.  
The grantees  university law professors and their students  will also research &quot;the 
optimal design and constitutional validity of state legislation that would strengthen 
legal procedures for obtaining such reimbursement of health care costs from the 
tobacco industry.&quot;  Additional government 
funding for the project is provided by the 
Massachusetts Department of Public Health 
($324,500 annually) and the Americans With 
Disabilities Act ($284,804).
<P>The plaintiffs lawyers who take such cases on behalf of state governments can 
well afford their own legal research, especially since they stand to earn hundreds of 
millions of dollars in contingency fees.  It is likely 
that they will benefit more than any tobacco smoker, courtesy of NCI and other 
government agencies.  
<P>Florida reports one final bit of 
&quot;progress&quot; to the CDC.  The Coalition intends to 
use federal tax dollars to &quot;actively support 
employee litigation against employers who fail to implement meaningful smoking policies.&quot; 
 FDHRS recently recruited an attorney who will help employees harass their 
employers who fail to enact politically correct 
anti-smok<BR>
ing policies along the lines suggested by the state coalition.  
<P>
<P><B>Resurrecting Alcohol Prohibition</B>
<P>The Robert Wood Johnson Foundation recently announced a new four year, 
$10.2 million grant program that follows the same format as its &quot;Tobacco Free States&quot; 
grant program.  The new program will fund statewide political coalitions as well as local 
coalitions to encourage alcohol prohibition.  Like the anti-smoking programs, this one 
contains plenty of rhetoric about children.  Indeed, the program's name is &quot;Reducing 
Underage Drinking Through Community and State Coalitions.&quot;  But the public 
policies highlighted in its brochure affect 
<I>everyone</I>  legal as well as underage drinkers.
<P>For example, among government interventions &quot;shown to be effective&quot; are 
&quot;restrictions on the distribution of alcohol&quot; 
through state government monopoly liquor stores, regulatory limits on &quot;outlet density,&quot; and 
the elimination of advertising.  Perhaps because State liquor monopolies charge higher 
prices than private, competitive liquor stores, 
the Foundation considers them a positive benefit to adult purchasers of liquor.  
Similarly, limits on competitive advertising are sure 
to lead to higher liquor prices.  But won't limits on &quot;outlet density&quot; increase accidents 
as purchasers drive further away to drink?    
<P>Another &quot;effective&quot; intervention, 
according to RWJF, is &quot;increases in taxes and 
the relative price of alcoholic beverages.&quot;  
This, too, is proposed for the sake of children, 
even though sales to minors are already illegal.  Increased taxes and the other proposed 
laws and regulations apply to all liquor sales.   RWJF literature says nothing about 
parental responsibility. 
<P>The last paragraph of the RWJF grant announcement offers this disclaimer:  
&quot;Grant funds may not be used ... for lobbying 
or otherwise attempting to influence legislation.&quot;  This statement cannot be accepted 
at face value when the primary purpose of the program is to fund statewide coalitions 
<I>of lobbyists</I> whose mission is to enact 
prohibitionist policies.  Grantees are &quot;expected 
to mobilize existing or new statewide or local coalitions&quot; to enact higher alcohol 
excise taxes and other legislated restrictions on alcohol consumption.   Among the 
&quot;selection criteria&quot; for the grants is the 
&quot;<I>political feasibility</I>&quot; of the state's project (emphasis added).
<P>The RWJF brochure claims its prohibitionist policy proposals are &quot;seen as the 
most successful approaches.&quot;  Perhaps this is 
why it has allocated $10.2 million to finance such campaigns in twelve states.  
<P>
<P><B>Conclusions</B>
<P>It is illegal to spend tax funds on partisan political activity.  Yet this is what the CDC 
is doing when it allocates hundreds of millions of tax dollars for anti-smoking coalition 
building.  These amounts are comparable to the amount spent on congressional campaigns. 
 Similarly, individuals and organizations that contribute to candidates cannot deduct 
their contributions from their taxes.  But a tax-exempt foundation like the Robert 
Wood Johnson Foundation spends millions of dollars constructing a &quot;political 
infrastructure&quot; for assorted prohibitionist movements 
in dozens of states.
<P>Self-interest reinforces ideology in the actions of the major health charities  the 
ACS, AHA, and ALA.  As documented in this study and in my book, 
<I>Unhealthy Charities</I> (Basic Books, 1994), with James T. 
Bennett, health charities receive federal 
government funds to build political coalitions.  They, 
in turn, lobby state legislatures to require educational programs for adults and children 
to be administered by   none other than the health charities themselves.  
<P>The CDC's reputation is built on its work in health research, education, and 
disease innoculation.  By undertaking to finance 
lobbying campaigns sponsored by various tax-exempt organizations, it is denying 
Americans the right to make their own decisions with regard to personal behaviors that 
have been deemed politically-incorrect.  And it is diverting millions of dollars from 
important disease research.  This abuse of 
taxpayers' dollars should be stopped.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 6 -->

<P><B>Briefly</B>Noted<BR>
In response to the increasing practice on the part of some large foundations, including the ROBERT WOOD 
JOHNSON FOUNDATION, of using grant monies to &quot;leverage&quot; public funds, the Pennsylvania General Assembly is considering a 
measure that would sharply curtail the ability of state agencies to solicit or receive funding from nonprofit foundations.  More details to 
be provided in future issues.
<P>
<P>Liberal intellectuals and labor leaders are attempting to revive the old alliance between organized labor and &quot;progressive&quot; academia. 
 Recently, a series of &quot;teach-ins&quot;  modeled on the anti-war conferences of the Vietnam era  have been held at various 
campuses around the country as a means of inspiring students and professors to devote more of their energy toward helping the union agenda. 
 At a Columbia University event, AFL-CIO President John Sweeney declared, &quot;We need your help in telling millions of 
unrepresented workers that while it takes a village to raise a child, it takes a union to get a raise.&quot;  
[<I>New York Times</I>]
<P>
<P>The CENTER FOR EQUAL OPPORTUNITY in Washington has published a new monograph entitled 
<I>Race and the Criminal Justice System:  How Race Affects Jury 
Trials</I>.  It includes a series of essays that debate whether race continues to skew justice in 
the courtroom and what role, if any, race should play in jury selection.  Contributors include Walter Berns, Joan Biskupic, 
Randall Kennedy and Jeffrey Rosen.  The final essay by Robert Lerner suggests, contrary to conventional wisdom, that blacks are 
actually more likely than whites to be acquitted in jury trials for most felonies.  Contact the Center:  202-639-0803 / www.ceousa.org
<P>
<P>During the recent presidential campaign, press reports revealed that the Clinton administration exploited a Justice 
Department program called &quot;Citizenship USA&quot; (designed to accelerate the naturalization process for new citizens) in order to register 
hordes of new Democratic voters before election day.  Further reports show that the White House gave most of the Citizenship USA 
work to liberal &quot;community advocacy groups&quot; like the UNITED NEIGHBORHOOD ORGANIZATION, which has close ties to both 
the President and Mrs. Clinton.
<P>
<P>A &quot;third wave&quot; of free market think tanks has begun to emerge.  Following the rise of Washington and state-based policy 
groups (the first and second waves respectively), the ALLEGHENY INSTITUTE in Pittsburgh is blazing the way for a new generation 
of market-oriented groups that will focus on local issues.  The Institute's executive director, Gerry Bowyer, writing in The 
Heritage Foundation's <I>Insider</I> newsletter, reports that the new group is working to restructure the government of Allegheny 
County, Pennsylvania, focusing on privatization efforts (including privatization of an airport and property assessments) and deregulation. 
 Contact the Institute:  412-937-4426.
<P>
<P><I>Z Magazine</I>, the entertaining publication for the unreconstructed leftist, is in trouble.  An urgent appeal warns that 
&quot;various circumstances&quot;  including the fact that Z hadn't filed IRS forms for four years  have put the brash magazine  
&quot;publication home&quot; of such notables as Noam Chomsky, Barbara Ehrenreich, and Sara Diamond  in a precarious situation.  
Emergency appeal donations may be sent to 18 Millfield Street, Woods Hole, MA  02543.
<P>
<P>Drugs and Welfare:  Billionaire financier George Soros, prime benefactor of the drug legalization movement, plans to give 
$50 million to immigration rights organizations across the country.  He is doing so in response to the welfare reform legislation 
enacted earlier this year, which Soros believes to be unjust and part of a &quot;mean-spirited attack on immigrants.&quot;  The funds will be 
dispersed through his newest charitable foundation, the EMMA LAZARUS FUND.  
<P>
<P>Can't we just get along:  In a full-page ad in the 
<I>Nation</I> magazine, five environmental groups (Earthtrust, Endangered 
Species Project, Friends of Animals, Marine Mammal Fund, and Sea Shepherds Conservation Society) attack GREENPEACE 
for supporting what they call the &quot;Dolphin Death Bill,&quot; which they claim weakens the U.S. dolphin protection law.  The groups 
accuse Greenpeace of being AWOL in the tuna/dolphin battle while &quot;mailing millions of letters appealing to the public to `save the dolphins.'&quot; 
 Thousands of dolphins will die, they say, because Greenpeace acts &quot;hypocritically.&quot;  For our part, we've always been 
more concerned about the neglected rights of the tuna.<HR>
