<img src="/crc/images/hdr-ap.gif"><br>
</center>
<I>December, 1996</I><BR>
<h2>Coporate Philanthropy: A Reexamination</h2>
<hr>

<I>Corporations and corporate foundations gave an estimated $6.11 billion to nonprofit organizations in 1994. 
 This represented 4.7 percent of total charitable giving ($129.88 billion).  Of this $6.11 billion, the 
largest corporations gave at least $35.78 million to public-affairs organizationsgroups that seek to influence 
public policy in such areas as the environment, taxes, and regulation.
<P>While $35.78 million is a relatively minor amount, public-affairs groups operating with small budgets 
have successfully lobbied government to reallocate billions of dollars in private-sector resources.  This is a 
central contention of Capital Research Center's 
</I>Patterns of Corporate Philanthropy<I>, an annual study of 
corporate public-affairs giving.  CRC research associate 
<B>Austin Fulk</B> summarizes findings from this year's 
tenth anniversary edition, which examines corporate giving in 1994.
<P>This issue also features an essay on corporate giving by 
<B>William E. Simon</B>, a CRC trustee and president 
of the John M. Olin Foundation who served as Secretary of the Treasury to Presidents Nixon and Ford.
<P>Six observers of corporate philanthropy respond: 
<B>Kristen A. Avansino</B>, President of the E.L. 
Wiegand Foundation; <B>Albert Dunlap</B>, Chairman of Sunbeam Corporation; economist 
<B>Milton Friedman</B>; <B>Heather R. Higgins</B>, Director of the Randolph Foundation; 
<B>Henry Manne</B>, Professor of Law at George Mason 
University; and <B>Dorothy S. Ridings</B>, President of the Council on Foundations.
<P>Finally, CRC Visiting Fellow <B>Martin Morse 
Wooster</B> reviews <B>John Hood</B>'s new book, 
</I>The Heroic Enterprise: Business and the Common Good<BR>
<B>Taking Philanthropy Seriously:
<P>Giving as Though Our Future
<P>Depended on It
<P>by William E. Simon</B>
<P>
<P>It is a sad commentary, but I see many American 
business leaders financing the destruction of freedom.  They 
have been doing so for decades.  I don't mean that they 
give enormous amounts of money to political candidates 
who regularly vote against the interests of a competitive 
free economy (they do, but that is another matter).
<P>I am referring to their support of nonprofit 
organizations that are controlled by what Irving Kristol has called 
the &quot;new class.&quot;  This elite, hostile to the fundamental 
principles of our society, happily devours the fruits of 
capitalism while working to poison the tree that bears them.
<P><I>continued on page 2</I><BR>
<B>Patterns of Corporate Philanthropy,
<P>Tenth Edition:
<P>Funding the Clinton Agenda
<P>by Austin Fulk</B>
<P>
<P>1994 marked a pivotal point in the history of 
American politics.  After two years of the Clinton presidency and 
forty years of Democratic control of the House of 
Representatives, voters turned out to elect Republican majorities 
in both Houses of Congress.
<P>Anger at Clinton Administration plans to expand the 
size of government fueled voter upheaval: a failed attempt 
to nationalize the health-care system, tax increases despite 
a Clinton campaign promise for &quot;middle-class tax cuts,&quot; 
and continued assaults on private property rights 
alienated many voters and led to the Democrats' reversal of fortune.
<P><I>continued on page 7
<!-- Generation of story text from PM publication page 2 -->

</I><BR>
Alternatives in Philanthropy<BR>
<B>Taking Philanthropy Seriously</B>
<P><I>(continued from page 1)</I><BR>
be viewed as &quot;progressive&quot; and &quot;socially responsible,&quot; no matter to what asinine end 
this leads them.  They are in mortal terror of being 
branded &quot;conservative&quot; or &quot;rapacious&quot; or &quot;insensitive&quot; or 
&quot;exploiters&quot; and of losing their seats at the annual dinners 
of organizations dedicated to their destruction.
<P>
<P><B>The Entrepreneurial Spirit</B>
<P>This was not the attitude of the great entrepreneurs 
who built American enterprise.  Andrew Carnegie did not 
yearn to be the guest of honor at a dinner of the Industrial 
Workers of the World.  He had faith in the system of 
private enterprise and worked to produce, as cheaply as 
possible, the steel to build the railroads, bridges, and skyscrapers 
of a rising America.
<P>John D. Rockefeller wanted to make transportat<BR>
&quot;Business leaders . . . have provided much of the driving energy of 
the anti-capitalist movement today.  They have done it not only by avoiding 
the struggle, but, worse yet, by financing their opponents.&quot;<BR>
ion and illumination available to every family.  Henry Ford 
wanted to give millions of Americans a chance at low-cost 
transportation.  Jim Hill envisioned a northern empire across 
the great plains, built a great railroad without 
government subsidies, and brought settlers to produce wheat 
for America's bread.
<P>These were tough-minded men, and some of the 
things they did invited legitimate criticism; but they never 
wavered in their faith that freedom of enterprise would 
build a great and powerful and prosperous America.
<P>By contrast, a distressing number of today's 
non-owning managers of industry act like bureaucrats in 
three-piece suits whose goal is to get along without making waves.  
If Carnegie had had that mentality, he would have retired 
as the chief telegrapher of the Pennsylvania Railroad, 
and somebody elseI hopewould have forged the rails 
to cross our prairies and made the steel plate for our 
Great White Fleet.
<P>Business leaders who lack commitment to the virtues 
of our system are almost as guilty as those whose goal is 
to destroy that system.  They urge business to keep a 
&quot;low profile&quot; and scoff at the free-market ideal as an 
obsolete notion in this modern age.  They have an obsession 
with being accepted and toasted by the most vocal of 
their <BR>
<B>Fueling the War on Freedom</B>
<P>The keenest and most prophetic analysis of this 
problem was offered half a century ago by Joseph Schumpeter in 
his landmark work <I>Capitalism, Socialism, and 
Democracy</I>.  It was he who first pointed out that capitalism, by its 
very success in raising the standard of living to 
unprecedented heights, would weaken the institutions necessary for 
its survival, giving way to a centralized socialist 
bureaucracy that would exploit the productive capacity created by 
private enterprise.
<P>Schumpeter gloomily concluded that the leaders of 
capitalism would likely absorb the slogans of radicalism and 
let themselves be converted &quot;to a creed hostile to [their] 
very existence&quot; because they were &quot;rapidly losing faith in 
[their] own creed.&quot;  &quot;This is verified,&quot; he wrote, &quot;by the 
characteristic manner in which particular capitalist interests 
and bourgeoisie as a whole behave when facing direct attack. 
 They talk and plead or hire people to do it for them.  
They snatch at every chance of compromise.  They are ever 
ready to give in.  They never put up a fight under the flag of 
their own ideals and their interests.&quot;
<P>There are, in my view, several different reasons 
why business leaders act this way.  One is simply lack 
of awareness.  They are too busy running their businesses 
to know what is going on in the intellectual world about 
them, unless their companies are specifically attacked.  
Such ignorance can well be economically fatal.
<P>Others, while perhaps aware of the drumbeat of 
attacks on capitalism, are simply unable to understand why 
those attacks are invalid.  Perhaps it sounds reasonable to them 
to believe that capitalism is some kind of scourge and 
affliction which has beset much of the world while ignoring 
the fact that people in non-Western countries yearn for 
the same chance at freedom and prosperity.
<P>Some may be aware of the merits of our system but 
have no inkling of how to fight back.  After all, they are 
in business, not in battles over public opinion, and they 
are usually less confident with the written word than is 
the intellectual class from which the attack springs.  So 
they flee the field of battle.
<P>Still others simply may not want to get involved.  
They simply assume that, somehow, the system of which they 
are a part will survive the attacks of its enemies without 
their participation.  Only when the attack hits home do they 
wake upand then it may be too late.  Edmund Burke's 
famous maxim is particularly apt: &quot;All that is necessary for 
the forces of evil to win in the world is for good men to 
do nothing.&quot;
<P>The worst are those who yield before the assaults of 
their enemies.  They long to 
<!-- Generation of story text from PM publication page 3 -->

critics.
<P>Two decades ago, at the American Enterprise 
Institute, Robert Bork observed that &quot;These are the people thought 
of by the general public and by critics of the corporate 
system as bold, rapacious, cunning leaders, the Machiavellis of 
our society.&quot;  In reality, however, &quot;one finds many of them to 
be docile, apprehensive, defensive, and unsure of how 
to respond to sharp unrelenting attacks. . . .  It is as though 
a large fraction of the [business] community . . . wants 
to make preemptive concessions, as if they meet not to plan 
a fight against a wrongheaded movement but to discuss 
how best to negotiate the terms of surrender.&quot;
<P>Bork went on to concludeand it is a conclusion I 
very much sharethat business can never regain its moral 
legitimacy until business leaders can convince the rest of 
the country that they believe in that legitimacy themselves. 
 Their defensive posture &quot;will earn only the contempt of 
the enemies of corporations and capitalism, while leading 
the large, relatively indifferent majority to suppose that 
the <BR>
&quot;Every corporation should spend every dollar of every contribution 
with the same care it devotes to employee pay and new equipment.  
Decisions about corporate contributions should be made on the same level, and 
by many of the same people, as decisions about corporate strategy 
and investment.&quot;<BR>
essage.
<P>A second step is for business leaders themselves to 
play an active role on the boards of foundations that 
their businesses have made possible.  The most fatal of errors 
is for men and women who have proven themselves in 
the profit-making sector to accept a foundation board seat 
and then sit back while professional foundation managers 
tell them the &quot;right&quot; thing to do.
<P>There are many able and conscientious foundation 
executives like Michael Joyce of the Bradley Foundation 
and Jim Piereson of Olin; but for every Joyce and 
Piereson, there seem to be dozens who practice the foundation 
equivalent of &quot;pack journalism&quot;managers who, with aims 
far different from those of their foundations' creators, make 
a career of trying to awe their directors with their 
superior wisdom and grander vision of the &quot;public interest.&quot;  
These people are very good at manipulating words and symbols 
so that the business director or trustee feels almost ashamed 
to <BR>
critics must be right: if capitalism were a positive good 
and worth defending, business leaders would not be so ready 
to compromise and, if need be, to capitulate.&quot;
<P>Alas, it is these same business leaders who have 
provided much of the driving energy of the anti-capitalist 
movement today.  They have done it not only by avoiding the 
struggle, but, worse yet, by financing their opponents.
<P>In 1995, American corporations gave out more than 
$7 billion in charitable contributions, much of it for 
very worthwhile charities like hospitals, the Red Cross, 
and religious institutions; but millions upon millions of 
dollars also are handed out to politically activist nonprofit 
organizations.  This money is lavished on groups whose 
actions show them to be contemptuous of democratic 
capitalism and enthusiastic about the squalor of collectivism.
<P>In 1977, the late Henry Ford II, grandson of the man 
who pioneered the low-cost car and the $5 daily wage, 
resigned from the board of the Ford Foundation, writing that 
&quot;The Foundation is a creature of capitalism&quot; but that &quot;it is 
hard to discern recognition of this fact in anything the 
Foundation does.  It is even more difficult to find an 
understanding of this in many of the institutions, particularly the 
universities, that are the beneficiaries of the Foundation's 
grant programs.&quot;  He urged his fellow trustees to &quot;examine 
the question of our obligations to our economic system and 
to consider how the foundation, as one of the system's 
most prominent offspring, might act most wisely to 
strengthen and improve its progenitor.&quot;  Asked why this had 
happened, he replied, &quot;I tried for thirty years to change it from 
within, to no avail.&quot;
<P>This is an all too familiar pattern in our largest 
foundations and corporations.  What a tragedy it would be 
if capitalism should prove to be the engine of its own 
destruction through its mindless support of those who would 
tear it down.
<P>
<P><B>What Can Be Done?</B>
<P>Fortunately, much can be done.  The first step is 
to awaken business leaders to the nature and magnitude of 
the threat and stiffen their backbones for the battle.
<P>There are many ways to do this, but there is no 
substitute for the determined leadership of those who are respected 
in the world of business.  My model here is the late John 
M. Olin, whose foundation I have the honor to head.  John 
Olin built a great industrial enterprise but never lost sight of 
the fundamentals of a free society.  When he endowed a 
foundation, he made it clear that its mission was to preserve 
our freedoms and strengthen our resolve in the unending 
battle we face.  When he spoke to businessmen, he 
unhesitatingly came down hard on the vital importance of preserving 
this system.  Others must come forward to repeat that m<BR>
<I>continued on page 4
<!-- Generation of story text from PM publication page 4 -->

</I><BR>
Alternatives in Philanthropy<BR>
<B>Taking Philanthropy Seriously</B>
<P><I>(continued from page 3)</I><BR>
question the destination and use of grant money.
<P>Foundation trustees must, in a sense, become 
philosophical detectives, cutting through jargon and rhetoric to 
understand what is really being proposed.  Business 
people, whether they serve on foundation boards and 
corporate contributions committees or make contributions on 
their own, must take their obligations seriously.  They must 
learn to be as careful in their contributions as they are in 
their personal investments.
<P>Third, those of us who believe in the great principles 
of liberty upon which our society was founded must take 
pains to see that corporate and foundation gifts are directed to 
the support of institutions and individuals who are working 
to maintain freedom.  When I was Treasury Secretary, 
I offered this thought in a speech to corporate public 
affairs officers: Counsel your principals not to support 
organizations whose aim is to destroy our freedoms.  Unless 
corporations and business leaders steer their corporate gifts 
to institutions that are helping to maintain freedom, the 
largesse of the free enterprise system will continue to 
finance its own destruction.
<P>
<P><B>A Reaffirmation</B>
<P>The task of business is to ensure that voices are 
raised effectively from philanthropic institutions to support a 
free society.  The American people will always choose 
freedom once they understand the implications of the 
collectivist alternatives.
<P>Capitalism has no duty to subsidize its enemies.  It 
does have a duty to support the efforts of those individuals 
and institutions which cherish our freedoms and the values 
of Western civilization.  Every corporation should 
spend every dollar of every contribution with the same care 
it devotes to employee pay and new equipment.  
Decisions about corporate contributions should be made on the 
same level, and by many of the same people, as decisions 
about corporate strategy and investment.
<P>Corporations and foundations ought to apply 
zero-based budgeting to their contributions.  Instead of having 
an assistant treasurer just write the annual check, 
business leaders should look closely to see whether their 
donations are still serving a useful purpose or whether they could 
be put to better use elsewhere.
<P>Years ago, Joseph Schumpeter was asked whether 
his gloomy analysis of the impending decline of capitalism 
was defeatist.  He replied with some indignation, &quot;the 
report that a given ship is sinking is not defeatist, only the spirit 
in which this report is received can be defeatist.  The crew 
can sit down and drink.  But it can also rush to the pumps.&quot;<BR>
<B>Kristen A. Avansino
<P>President and Executive Director
<P>The E.L. Wiegand Foundation</B>
<P>
<P>The business of nonprofits is the business of 
for-profits plus altruism.  More than ever, responsible giving 
and responsible disbursement are the bywords of 
exemplary philanthropy.  But today's philanthropic climate also 
demands that we repeat two caveats: Henry Ward 
Beecher warned donors, &quot;Do not give, as many rich men do, like 
a hen that lays an egg, and then cackles.&quot;  William Simon 
has warned trustees, &quot;Do not accept a foundation board seat 
and then sit back.&quot;
<P>Avansino: &quot;While a grant proposal may pull at a trustee's heartstrings,
<P>a sound business assessment is mandatory.&quot;<BR>
Management expert Peter Drucker reminds us that 
&quot;leadership is a foul-weather job.&quot;  The trustee who 
exercises real leadership must have a discerning mind and heart. 
 Every decision, however minuscule, embodies a 
fiduciary responsibility that transcends business as usual.  The 
trustee must understand the foundation's mission and have a 
profound respect for the donor whose wealth created 
the foundation.
<P>The trustee should assure that the financial 
mandates inherent in the for-profit world are also brought to bear 
on the foundation.  Questions regarding the foundation's 
fiscal health, management practices, efficiency, and 
effectiveness should be addressed, as should the &quot;buzzwords&quot; of 
the '90sduplication of services and accountability.  In 
short, while a grant proposal may pull at the trustee's 
heartstrings, a sound business assessment is mandatory.
<P>In the end, the business of nonprofit grant review 
should resemble business itself.  Philanthropy, the cornerstone 
of a civil society, demands no less.
<P>
<P><B>Albert Dunlap
<P>Chairman and CEO
<P>Sunbeam Corporation</B>
<P>
<P>Business is not a social experiment.  Far too 
many business leaders lose sight of what should be the goal 
of corporations in a capitalistic environmentlong-term 
profit optimization.  This objective creates and promotes 
the 
<!-- Generation of story text from PM publication page 5 -->

competitiveness which is essential for America to 
prosper in a global economy.
<P>One of the major underlying problems with 
corporate philanthropy is that most executives are self-serving 
and shortsighted.  Their actions, however, have long-term 
consequences for which they either do not care or do 
not understand.  They thirst for acceptance and 
recognition from the &quot;elite&quot; and fear criticism from the public.  
In today's environment, where the press is quick to attack 
and even sensationalize controversial views and decisions, 
most business leaders politicize their actions to avoid such 
criticism.
<P>If capitalism is to be protected and American business 
is to thrive, business leaders must be educated as to 
the completeness of their actions and their long-term effect 
on free enterprise.  They must then have the conviction to 
make decisions for the good of the whole, even if those 
who benefit resist due to their ignorance.  The price of 
leadership is criticism.
<P>
<P><B>Dr. Milton Friedman
<P>Senior Research Fellow
<P>Hoover Institution</B>
<P>
<P>As William Simon stresses, the social function of 
a business corporation is to produce goods and services 
that customers wish to buy, and to do so at the lowest 
possible cost.  Its function is not to serve as a philanthropic 
or charitable organization.  The only justification for 
philanthropy is tax avoidance: under present law, 
contributions up to a specified fraction of income are deductible 
in calculating income subject to tax, whereas dividend 
payments are not.  Accordingly, a one dollar reduction 
in dividends enables corporations to make a contribution 
of more than one dollar at the same cost.
<P>Friedman: &quot;I see little reason to expect the business community 
to change its current suicidal behavior with respect to philanthropy.&quot;<BR>
lative and rights can be created and changed.  
Importantly, too, since men are naturally good, evil can't 
come from them but rather wholly from the effects of evil 
social forces (e.g., poverty, capitalism, racism, and sexism).  
These forces must be countered by massive changes to 
society, essentially through the instrument of government.
<P>As a culture, we have largely succumbed to this 
second <BR>
The individual stockholder benefits if and only if 
the contributions are to causes or organizations that he or 
she wishes to support.  Except for closely held 
corporations with few stockholders, the way to assure that outcome 
is one Warren Buffet adopted many years ago for 
Berkshire-Hathaway.  Dividend checks to stockholders are 
accompanied by a statement along the following lines: &quot;In 
addition to paying a dividend, Berkshire-Hathaway will 
contribute X dollars per share of stock to charitable causes.  
Please return the enclosed form telling us whom you would 
like your share of those contributions to be given.&quot;
<P>Unfortunately, few corporations have followed that 
excellent example.  Short of their doing so or of tax 
changes that either permit the deductibility of dividends in 
calculating corporate taxes or deny the deductibility of 
charitable contributions, I see little reason to expect the 
business community to change its current suicidal behavior 
with respect to philanthropy.
<P>
<P><B>Heather R. Higgins
<P>Director
<P>The Randolph Foundation</B>
<P>
<P>From earliest childhood, I recall my frustrated 
father commenting in disgust that when it came to philanthropy 
or serving on boards, &quot;Businessmen park their brains at 
the door.&quot;  Sadly, experience repeatedly bears out this 
observation.
<P>Simon is correct in his analysis of the various factors 
that influence this behavior: preoccupation, ignorance, 
timidity, naivet&eacute;, and shallowness.  I would go even 
further, however, and argue that behind these characteristics lie 
a vast philosophical change which has affected most 
Americans, not just business leaders: a complete reorientation 
in the basic assumptions of who we are and how we relate 
to the world around us.
<P>The classical view, held even by deists, was that we 
were creatures of Goda relationship that had vast 
implications for our understandings of right and wrong, and for the 
role of government.  In such a world view, man is neither 
good nor bad but capable of choosing either.  As defined by 
God or natural law, there is both truth and a baseline for 
good that exist outside of man.  And there are basic rights, 
which also exist outside of man and delimit the capacity of 
others to encroach upon him while creating obligations 
toward others.
<P>In contrast, the modern view holds that man himself 
is good and therefore the arbiter of the good.  Since each 
can define his own understanding of what is right, truth 
is re<BR>
