<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Alternatives in Philanthropy August 1996 -- CRC
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/crc/images/bg.gif">
<a href="/crc/images/sidebar.map"><img src="/crc/images/sidebar.gif" alt="Navigation Bar" border="0" align="left" ISMAP></a>
<blockquote>
<center>
<img src="/crc/images/hdr-ap.gif"><br>
</center>
<P>
<i>August 1996<BR></i>
<h2>Charity and Responsibility</h2>
<p>
<h3>CRC Hosts Washington Conference</h3>
<p>
<p>
<DD>On June 25, Capital Research Center hosted a 
conference on the theme of &quot;Charity and Responsibility.&quot;  Some 
100 guests from private and family foundations, 
corporations, think tanks, and the media gathered at the University 
Club in Washington, D.C. to discuss the prospects for 
strengthening private charity and reforming the welfare state.
<DD>Capital Research Center president <B>Terrence 
Scanlon</B> opened the event by remarking that &quot;our country 
cannot have a prosperous and free economy and a 
responsible government unless we have strong and independent 
social institutions.&quot;  He criticized the way that many 
tax-exempt organizations in recent years have undermined the 
American tradition of charity and responsibility by 
promoting governmentrather than private and 
voluntaryapproaches to public problems: &quot;Rather than provide a 
valuable public service that government cannot or should 
not provide, many nonprofits mobilize activists and lobby 
for higher taxes, more regulation, and more welfare 
programsthe same programs that have repeatedly failed our 
neediest citizens.&quot;<BR>
<H4>The View from Capitol Hill</H4>
<DD>The morning keynote speakers were 
Representatives <B>David M. McIntosh</B> (R-IN) and 
<B>Ernest J. Istook</B> (R-OK), sponsors of last year's &quot;Istook Amendment,&quot; a measure which would have limited taxpayer funding of 
nonprofit organizations that engage in political advocacy.
<DD>Rep. McIntosh criticized the welfare state for 
undermining America's tradition of community-based 
problem-solving.  He also endorsed the idea of a tax credit for 
charitable giving.  This would allow individual taxpayers to 
directly earmark a portion of their federal tax dollars to 
charities that help the needy while requiring dollar-for-dollar cuts 
in government welfare programs.
<DD>Noting that &quot;charity begins at home, not in the 
Capitol building,&quot; Rep. Istook called for greater exposure of 
nonprofit organizations that receive taxpayer support 
while lobbying for more welfare programs.  He argued 
that Congress and the media must educate the public about 
the role of advocacy groups so that voters will demand 
passage of legislation such as the failed Istook Amendment: 
&quot;The invisibility of many advocacy groups makes it difficult 
to build public support for reform.  The public tends to 
think all nonprofits are good, but many nonprofits are 
essentially lobbying arms of the government.&quot;<BR>
<H4>The Media's perspective</H4>
<P>Former Attorney General <B>Edwin Meese III</B> chaired 
a lively panel on the media's coverage of philanthropy.  
Five speakers who have written extensively on nonprofit 
organizations from a variety of perspectives argued about 
changes in the nonprofit sector and their impact on the kinds 
of stories they write.  Panelists generally agreed that the 
media pays ample attention to &quot;horror stories&quot; in 
philanthropy, such as the recent United Way scandal, but that the 
day-to-day work of charities and grantmakers goes largely 
unreported.
<DD><B>Jody Curtis</B>, executive editor of the <B>Council on 
Foundations</B>' <I>Foundation News + 
Commentary</I>, said that her publication has focused on offering &quot;how-to&quot; advice to donors and has generally avoided controversial issues 
in philanthropy.  Future editions, however, might 
explore more contentious subjects, such as direct-service 
giving versus advocacy or highlight examples of failure in 
philanthropy<BR>
<DD><B>Roberta d'Eustachio</B>, president and founder of 
the soon-to-be-launched <I>American Benefactor 
Magazine</I>, contended that wealthy individuals need entertaining and 
easy-to-understand articles that will encourage them to 
become donors and create foundations.  She emphasized that 
benefactors sometimes need help in clarifying their 
philanthropic values but cautioned those who advise them to 
&quot;let 1,000 flowers bloom&quot; and not try to choose donors' causes.
<DD><B>Laurence Jarvik</B>, editor of CRC's newsletters 
<I>Foundation Watch</I> and <I>Culture Watch</I>, contended that a 
&quot;1960s sensibility permeates most large foundations,&quot; making 
them reluctant to reconsider long-standing grants programs aimed at 
expanding the welfare state.  Unless the media begins to subject the nonprofit sector 
to greater scrutiny and criticism, he contended, major foundations will 
not change their ways.
<DD><B>Adam Meyerson</B>, editor of the <B>Heritage 
Foundation</B>'s <I>Policy Review: The Journal of American 
Citizenship</I>, contended that the mainstream 
foundation world is wedded to the welfare state 
and is dominated by ideas that don't work.  Fortunately, he said, there are 
many small, community-based organizations that are successfully addressing 
problems such as crime, failing public schools, and family breakdown.  If 
journalists tell the story of these groups, they can serve as models for 
broader privately based initiatives.  (Meyerson's presentation appears on page five.)
<DD><B>Vince Stehle</B>, assistant editor of <I>The Chronicle of Philanthropy</I>,
opined that recent media scrutiny has helped make the nonprofit sector more professional and efficient. During the question-and-answer period, Meyerson 
observed that unlike private businesses, nonprofits do 
not have to satisfy customers to stay in business and, 
unlike government, they do not have to heed the will of voters. </I>Nonprofit accountability, he contended, requires close 
scrutiny by donors, the media, and watchdog groups.  
<B>Joseph Dolan</B> of the <B>Achelis and Bodman 
Foundations</B> suggested that evaluation of the effectiveness of nonprofit 
programs will become increasingly important as the needy come 
to rely on private programs rather than government welfare.
<P>
<P><H4>Replacing the Welfare State</H4>
<DD>A second panel, following lunch, explained why it's time for private 
initiative to replace failed government programs.  Chaired by 
<B>Daniel J. Popeo</B>, chairman and general counsel of 
the <B>Washington Legal Foundation</B>, it featured three leaders from private 
foundations.
<DD><B>Michael Cawley</B>, president of the <B>Samuel Roberts Noble 
Foundation</B> of Ardmore, Oklahoma, argued that 
the welfare state has &quot;stunted our desire to be charitable.&quot;  Nonetheless, he 
noted how Americans have time and again responded generously in the wake 
of natural disasters and tragedies such as the Oklahoma City bombing.  He 
expressed optimism that the genuinely needy would receive adequate 
assistance as government welfare is scaled back.
<DD><B>Heather Higgins</B>, director of the <B>Randolph 
Foundation</B>, contended that the welfare state's universal 
guarantee of benefits has undermined the desire of many recipients 
to change self-destructive behaviors.  The goal of 
charities, she said, &quot;should not be to replace government welfare 
but to do better than government programs.&quot;  She 
suggested that the media celebrate &quot;heroes&quot; in 
philanthropygrassroots organizers who are successfully addressing 
social problems through private initiativeso that 
average Americans can see that their efforts will make a difference.
<HR>
<BR>
<I>Heather Higgins: The goal of charities &quot;should not be to replace 
government welfare but to do better than government programs.&quot;</I><BR>
<HR>
<BR>
<B>James Piereson</B>, president of the <B>John M. Olin 
Foundation</B>, conjectured that we are in the early stages of 
major change in the philanthropic sector.  He urged supporters 
of a free society to develop a richer philosophy that 
encourages more voluntarism and a sense of moral obligation 
to others.  Arguing that lower taxes are essential to increased charitable giving, he expressed reservations about a 
charity tax credit, saying that it would undermine prospects for 
a lower, flat tax.  (Piereson's presentation appears on 
page four.) 
<BR>
<H3>Counsel for Charitable Giving</H3>
<DD>Also speaking at Capital Research Center's 
&quot;Charity and Responsibility&quot; conference were Daniel J. 
Popeo, chairman and general counsel of the Washington 
Legal Foundation (WLF) and a CRC trustee, and William 
J. Lehrfeld, a private attorney.  They announced 
the creation of the Counsel for Charitable Giving, 
whose aim is to provide technical assistance to 
individuals, families, and companies wishing to create 
charitable foundations to promote the cause of free enterprise 
and limited government.  For more information, call 
or write:
<P>
<CENTER><H5>Daniel J. Popeo<BR>
Chairman and General Counsel<BR>
Washington Legal Foundation<BR>
2009 Massachusetts Avenue, NW<BR>
Washington, DC 20036<BR>
(202) 588-0302<BR></H5>
</CENTER>
<P>
<H4>Alternatives in Philanthropy</H4><BR>
Fashioning a Conservative Alternative to Welfare<BR>
by Dr. James E. Piereson<BR>
Executive Director<BR>
 The John M. Olin Foundation
<P>
<DD>What is the conservative alternative to the welfare state? 
 If welfare were ended, how would we help the poor, the 
sick and disabled, and the elderly who now depend upon 
welfare programs?
<DD>These questions are often posed to those of us who 
reject the policies, institutions, and ideological assumptions 
of the welfare state.  Unfortunately, they do not admit of 
easy answers.  The fact that the welfare state has entangled 
itself in the lives of countless families and communities makes 
it all the more difficult to end without painful disruptions.
<DD>Some conservatives argue that we need a new 
public philosophy to challenge the world view of the welfare state. 
 This would emphasize duties as well as rights, the 
community as well as the individual, and private charity rather 
than government programs as the best means of 
addressing social problems.  Speaker Newt Gingrich has emphasized 
a &quot;conservative opportunity society,&quot; in which 
privately funded institutions assist the needy.  Others, borrowing 
the terminology of Eastern European reformers, stress 
rebuilding the institutions of &quot;civil society,&quot; which have 
been weakened by decades of reliance on government.  In 
both conceptions, private philanthropy is given the 
important task of bringing into place viable alternatives to 
welfare programs.
<DD>It is sometimes said that private institutions can 
better serve the poor and needy than the national government 
with <HR>
<BR>
&quot;We are in the relatively early stages of an important 
reform movement that has a long time yet to run its course.&quot;<HR>
<BR>
its array of welfare programs.  As a general proposition, 
I believe this is true.  Certainly, as Marvin Olasky has 
shown, it was true historically in America from colonial days to 
the Great Depression.
<DD>Yet the poverty problem, driven by misguided 
welfare policy, has exploded to a scale that will be very difficult 
for private institutions to manage.  It will be more effective 
to reform the welfare state in ways that begin to scale back 
the problem, rather than try to turn the task wholly over 
to private institutions.  Perhaps both can be done, but 
welfare reform appears to be a necessary condition for any success.
<DD>Is philanthropy being asked to do too much?  I suspect 
it is, especially when we consider the limited resources on 
our side.  Currently, the federal government spends 
some $400,000,000,000 annually on poverty programs, 
including AFDC, Medicaid, food stamps, rent supplements, and the like.  In 1995, individuals, foundations, and corporations donated some $144,000,000,000 to charitable 
institutions of various kinds.  My sense is that private 
philanthropyespecially conservative philanthropyis not 
yet substantial enough to carry out the assignment some 
have given it.
<DD>Still, I believe we are in the relatively early stages of 
an important reform movement that has a long time yet to
<HR>
<BR>
&quot;I have some reservations about an earmarked charitable deduction, 
as proposed by Senator Dole and others, because I fear it would 
undermine efforts to achieve a low flat tax.&quot;<HR>
<BR>
 
run its course.  We should remember that liberal 
philanthropy developed at the turn of the century in tandem with 
the Progressive movement.  It was built on the idea then 
in fashion that experts could identify social problems 
and design appropriate solutions that government would 
implement.  The cultural revolution of the 1960s drove 
liberal foundations ever deeper into this morass as new 
constituent groups were identified as clients of the welfare state.  
If conservatives are to reverse this trend, they will need 
to develop their own persuasive ideas.  This is now 
beginning to happen through the work of people like Marvin 
Olasky, Arianna Huffington, and groups like the 
Philanthropy Roundtable and the Capital Research Center.
<DD>I have given something of a mixed answer to the 
question posed earlier about philanthropy and the dismantling of 
the welfare state.  Bearing in mind Harry Truman's comment about the one-armed economist, let me lay down a 
few simple principles so that I do not end on a mixed note.  
It seems that several things should be done in tandem and 
in combination:
<UL>
<LI>First, public policy must be reformed, particularly 
in the areas of welfare and taxes, in order to scale back the 
size of the poverty problem and to encourage donations 
to charitable organizations.  Lower tax rates and reform 
of estate taxes would allow Americans to pass along 
more wealth to charities and to their families.  I have 
some reservations about an earmarked charitable deduction, 
as proposed by Senator Dole (R-KS) and others, because 
I fear it would undermine efforts to achieve a low flat tax.
<LI>Second, a conservative vision of philanthropy, 
linked to our understanding of a free society, must be advanced 
to challenge the reigning liberal philanthropy of such 
institutions as the Council on Foundations and the 
Ford, Rockefeller, and Pew foundations.  Such a vision, if 
aggressively pressed, will begin to increase donations to 
conservative organizations.
<LI>Third, we need to show that private-sector approaches, realistically conceived and assessed, are more effective than government programs in moving people 
out of poverty and into mainstream American life.  
Fortunately, many such models exist, but they need to be expanded 
and brought to the public's attention.
</UL>
<DD>With so much to do, there is no need for donors to fall 
into line behind one or another particular approach.  We are far better 
off if we encourage a healthy diversity that leaves room for donors to 
express their own interests in philanthropy.
<DD>The John M. Olin Foundation, for example, following the lead 
of our late donor, emphasizes public-policy studies in the areas of 
taxation, regulation, welfare, and national security, among others.  
Our general objective is to support individuals and institutions that work 
to strengthen our system of free enterprise and limited government.  
Most of our funds are directed to academic programs and research 
centers that support scholars, students, and researchers who address 
these issues.
<DD>Other donors, however, will want to emphasize 
different approaches.  Some will want to focus on direct assistance 
to the needy in their communities.  Others may want to 
support programs in the arts, education, history, literature, 
and philosophy.  This is all good and a sign of healthy 
growth in a movement just beginning to find its stride.
<DD>But let us not forget our larger goal, which is not 
to promote philanthropy for its own sake, but to strive 
to create for our children and grandchildren a country 
with more prosperity, more freedom, and greater moral 
confidence than the one we inherited.<BR>
<P>
<BR>
<BR>
<H4>The Trouble with Philanthropy</H4>
<BR>
by Adam Meyerson<BR>
Editor<BR>
<I>Policy Review</B></I>
<P>
<BR>
<DD>I come to you with the sad message that 
mainstream philanthropy is part of the problem in this country, not 
part of the solution.  There are many fine people in the 
mainstream foundations, and they fund many fine programs.  
But the foundation world has been dominatedand is 
still dominatedby ideas that do not work.
<DD>For the past 30 years, one of the central objectives 
of foundations has been to open opportunity for black 
Americans.  That is a noble, marvelous objective.  But what 
do foundations have to show for their efforts?  More black 
men are in jail or prison today than in college.
<DD>A second objective of foundations has been to 
revitalize cities and their economies.  Again, a noble objective.  
But New York City is bankrupt.  Washington, D.C. is bankrupt. 
 Boston, Cleveland, Philadelphia, Detroit, Chicago, 
Baltimore, and St. Louis have seen population declines of 25 
to 30 percent.
<DD>For 30 years, mainstream philanthropy has 
supposedly been standing up for children.  But more children 
are growing up in poverty today than 30 years ago.  We have 
an epidemic of child abuse.  Half a million children 
are languishing in state foster care.  And we've seen the 
collapse of the best safety net a child can havea mom and 
a dad who love him or her so much that they are willing to 
stay together despite marital difficulties.
<P>I submit that mainstream philanthropy has failed in 
all these areas because it has had the wrong ideas.  What 
are these ideas?  Here are eight of them:
<UL>
<LI>The failure to understand the importance of 
stable, two-parent families.  Philanthropy's focus has been 
on food, medical care, and income maintenance for the 
children of broken homes.  These are important, but it's 
more important to bring husbands and wives back together.
<LI>An overconcern with funding levels for schools 
and health and welfare programs and too little concern 
with performance levels.
<LI>Opposition to desperately needed reforms of 
the public-school system, such as the introduction of vouchers.
<LI>A bean-counting obsession with &quot;diversity,&quot; 
which has led public schools to set tragically low expectations 
for poor children, especially minorities.  The best 
affirmative action offers equal opportunity to all while holding 
everyone to the same high standards.
<LI>nThe perception of criminals as victims rather than victimizers.  This has undermined true rehabilitation, 
which must begin with repentance for committing evil.
<LI>A reluctance to say that certain kinds of 
behavior, such as teenage sex, abortion, promiscuity, or 
long-term welfare dependency, are morally wrong.
<LI>A misguided economic strategy, based on a 
misunderstanding of capitalism and wealth creation.  This has 
led to a disregard for the way that poor Americans are 
ravaged by high taxes, regulation, and crime.
<LI>A preoccupation with using the federal 
government to solve all our problems.  The great tragedy of 
government today is that it tries to do so much that it doesn't do 
anything well.
</UL>
<DD>The good news is that a tidal wave of social 
entrepreneurship is sweeping the country.  Ordinary Americans, 
through grassroots organizing, are solving problems that have 
perplexed mainstream foundations.  They're putting 
marriages back together, cutting crime, improving schools, and 
offering economic opportunity to the poor.  You can read 
their stories in our magazine, <I>Policy Review: The Journal 
of American Citizenship</I>.

<P>
--<br>
Terrence Scanlon, Publisher<br>
D.T. Oliver, Editor
<p>
<center>
Capital Research Center is a nonpartisan education and research organization
classified by the IRS as a 501(c)(3) public charity.
<p>
CRC, 727 15th Street, NW, Suite 800, Washington, DC, 20005 (202) 393-2600 http://www.capitalresearch.org
</center>
</blockquote>
</body>
