<TITLE>Business Relations Department -- Heritage</TITLE></HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<a name="top">
<center><img src="/heritage/thf_log2.gif"></a></center>
<p>

<H2>Business Relations Department</h2>

<hr>
<p>
The primary mission of the Business Relations department is to educate and mobilize the business community -- entrepreneurs, corporate leaders, trade associations, and activists -- on behalf of the  free enterprise/limited government policy agenda.  The department has coordinated briefings for industry groups on the current status of health care reform, telecommunications deregulation, trade, budget and tax reform, and deregulation.  
<p>
	In addition to meeting and briefing corporate representatives, the Business Relations department is working with industry coalitions to advance our agenda; coordinating working group meetings on the flat tax and regulatory reform; creating a "Resource Bank of Business" by identifying businessmen willing to speak, write, and testify on behalf of free enterprise/limited government policies; coordinating the activities of  our <a href="/heritage/dept_writeups/physc.html"><b>Physicians Council</b></a>; and launching a new <a href="#council"><b>Business Council</b></a> of the Heritage Foundation.
<p>
	In addition to smaller, informal briefings, we host Heritage's regular <b><i>Washington Policy Roundtable</i></b> meetings which bring Heritage experts, industry representatives, and policy makers together to discuss issues that are being debated on Capitol Hill.  <b><i>Roundtable</i></b> meetings this year have included:
<p>
<table border=0 cellspacing=10 cellpadding=10>
<tr align=left valign=top>
<td width=35%><b>February 28</b></td><td><b>The 1996 Congressional Agenda</b><br>
				Mike Franc, Director of Policy/Communications for Majority 					Leader Dick Armey</td></tr>
<tr align=left valign=top>
<td width=35%><b>March 14</b></td><td><b>The Freshman Agenda - Part II</b><br>
				Rep. Sam Brownback (R-KS) </td></tr>
<tr align=left valign=top>
<td width=35%><b>April 18</b></td><td><b>The FY97 Budget Resolution and Appropriations Process</b><br>

				Rep. Bob Livingston (R-LA) </td></tr>
<tr align=left valign=top>
<td width=35%><b>May 29</b></td><td><b>Renewing MFN for China</b><br>
				Rep. David Dreier (R-CA) </td></tr>
<tr align=left valign=top>
<td width=35%><b>September 20</b></td><td><b>Election '96</b><br>
James Glassman, <i>Washington Post</i> Columnist and "Capital Gang Sunday" Moderator, Kate O'Beirne, <i>National Review</i> Washington Editor and Heritage Distinguished Fellow</td></tr>

</table><p>


	Business Relations also launched two new fax publications this year to update and inform the business community.  Both are targeted to representatives in the corporate, public relations, legal, and association fields.  The <i>Business Bulletin</i> presents an occasional essay on topics of special interest to this community.  The first <i>Bulletin</i> on <a href="/heritage/dept_writeups/bb596.html">"Corporate Responsibility"</a> was authored by Rebecca Lukens Fellow <a href="/heritage/staff/wilson.htm">Mark Wilson</a> and timed for release just prior to the White House conference on corporate responsibility.  The second <i>Bulletin</i> highlights the Heritage publication on "<a href="/heritage/dept_writeups/bb696.html">How the Congress Won the Budget War</a>" and offers free copies of our new pocket-sized summary card on the paper.  <a href="/heritage/dept_writeups/octbrcal.html"><i>This Month at Heritage</i></a> is a faxed monthly calendar previewing upcoming Heritage lectures and events for the business community.

<p>
<h3><u>Business Relations Activities</u></h3>
<p><ul><b>
<li><a href="/heritage/dept_writeups/bb996.html">Business Bulletin</a>
<li><a href="#council">Business Council</a>
<li><a href="/heritage/dept_writeups/physc.html">Physicians Council</a>
<li><a href="/heritage/dept_writeups/octbrcal.html"><i>This Month at Heritage</i></a>
<li>Washington Policy Roundtable
<li>Working Groups
<ul type="ball">
<li><a href="#flattax">Flat Tax Transition Rules</a>
<li><a href="#regs">Regulatory Reform</a>
</ul></ul></b>

<p>
<a name="council">

<h3>Business Council</h3>
<p>
Heritage launched a Business Council, which will educate business executives, small business owners, and entrepreneurs about issues that directly affect them.  Our goal in establishing a Business Council of the Heritage Foundation is to identify a group of businessmen activists who, through their civic, business and community activities will help us leverage our own work on issues like tax and regulatory reform, health care, the federal budget, and education reform.
<p>
Members of the Council receive receive Heritage reports through the mail and by fax.  And serve as a source of information for Heritage experts on the impact government policies have on real people. 
 <p>
	If you are interested in joining the Business Council of The Heritage Foundation, please contact:  Bridgett Wagner, Director of Business Relations at 202/608-6050 or via email at <a href="mailto:wagnerb@heritage.org">wagnerb@heritage.org</a>.

<p>
<a name="flattax">
<h3>Flat Tax Transition Rules Working Group</h3>
<p>

	The Heritage Foundation and the Citizens for a Sound Economy Foundation have conducted a series of meetings that address various aspects of making a successful transition to a fundamentally reformed tax system.  These meetings will result in "white papers" and recommendations on moving towards effective transition rules. Topics have included: Accumulated Depreciation; Interest Deductibility; Health Care and Employee Benefits; Border Adjustability and Foreign Taxation; and Charitable Contributions.  If you are interested in learning more about these meetings or being added to our mailing list, please contact Bridgett Wagner at (202) 546-4400 or via e-mail at <a href="mailto:wagnerb@heritage.org">wagnerb@heritage.org</a>.

<p><a name="regs">
<h3>Regulatory Reform Working Group</h3>
<p>

	The Heritage Foundation leads the way in promoting regulatory reform by bringing together Hill Staff, lobbyists, and regulatory reform experts to address the ways in which we can make regulatory reform become a reality.  Topics include "How to Win the Environmental Debate," as well as other business, health and safety regulations.
<p>
